    <text id="B0430T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Jackson again writes to Hall about James Woods' appeal and his inability to
                    secure the necessary papers from his lawyer.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen and Abandoned Lands,<lb/>Office 4th Division, 9th
                    Sub-District, Virginia.
                    <name type="recipient"><abbr expan="Captain">Capt.</abbr> J.T.H. Hall<lb/><abbr
                            expan="Military Commissioner">Mil. Comr.</abbr><lb/>Woodstock</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1868-01-16"><abbr expan="January">Jan</abbr> 16th 1868</date>
                        <name type="place">Staunton, <abbr expan="Virginia">Va.</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Captain</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I have the honor to transmit enclosed herewith copies of letters referring to
                    appeal of James Woods, Elizabeth Furnace, Augusta <abbr expan="County">Co.</abbr>
                    <abbr expan="Virginia">Va</abbr>. Woods has again called at the office and prays
                    the papers be referred to proper officer in Rockbridge <abbr expan="County"
                    >Co.</abbr> who can obtain the asked for papers from Mr. James Dorman.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Very Respectfully<lb/><abbr expan="Your obedient servant">Yr obt
                        servt</abbr></salute>
                    <signed>Thos P. Jackson<lb/>Agent</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
